The paper deals with designing efficient communication primitives for radio networks, which falls under the category of networked and distributed systems (cs.NI) and distributed, parallel, and cluster computing (cs.DC). The use of collision-free layerings as a replacement for BFS-trees involves graph theory and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses randomized algorithms and their analysis, which falls under the category of information theory (cs.IT) and machine learning (cs.LG). Overall, the most likely categories are cs.NI and cs.DC, followed by cs.DS, cs.SI, and cs.IT.
